The United States economy added 213,000 jobs in June, indicating a strong labor market. The unemployment rate increased slightly, but this can be attributed to more individuals entering the labor force. Jobless claims remain at historic lows, indicating rare layoffs and strong job creation. The U.S. economy grew modestly in the winter but is expected to exceed a 4% pace in the second quarter, the fastest in almost four years. Americans' views of the job market remain positive, with 65% saying it is a good time to find a quality job. Manufacturing confidence is at a record high, and small business optimism is at its highest level in over 30 years. U.S. consumer sentiment and economic confidence have improved more than expected. Economic optimism among lower-income Americans has increased, and the IBD/TIPP Economic Optimism Index is at its second-highest level since 2004. Enrollment in the food stamp program has dropped to an eight-year low, and over $300 billion has been repatriated to the U.S. in the first quarter. U.S. retail sales have also exceeded forecasts, indicating a boost in economic growth.